geography.notes: lat-long estimated from map in paper and google maps; more precise value may be possible. See Luyssaert?

soil.notes: The region is part of the northern Clay Belt, a large physiographic region characterized by lacustrine clay deposits left by the proglacial lakes Barlow and Ojibway. This site type is dominant in the region and the soils are classified as Grey Luvisols.
Typically young and thin, rarely > 50 cm deep and often < 15 cm. They tend to be highly organic (loss on ignition 35-70%) and strongly acidic (pH 3.5-5.0).

Twenty soil series have been described in the site and grouped in two main orders: Entisol and Inceptisol. The most common soil subgroups are Ustoxic Dystropept, Typic Tropaquent, and Typic Tropopsamment.
